    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While some pests, like root-feeding larvae, can definitely damage roots and impair nutrient absorption, it's less common for them to *chemically* steal soil nutrients entirely. More often, heavy infestations stress the plant, making it less efficient at pulling in whatever nutrients are present. If you suspect physical damage, look closely for chewed tissue or signs of slime, but improper soil chemistry remains the most frequent culprit for these amber-and-green symptoms.",
